<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="36" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="10.[199,1772,1392,2201]" pageId="10" pageNumber="36">
Diagnosis: The species is closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Simon, 1901" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1901" box="[964,1441,1392,1431]" genus="H." pageId="10" pageNumber="36" rank="species" species="siiedicola">
<emphasis box="[964,993,1394,1422]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="36">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1020,1179,1392,1423]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="36">sııedicola</emphasis>
(Simon, 
<number box="[1349,1430,1393,1431]" pageId="10" pageNumber="36" value="1901.0">1901</number>
)
</taxonomicName>
. The male may be recognized by the longer strongly bent embolus and the shape of dorsal tibial apophysis, which is spike-like (bifurcate in 
<taxonomicName box="[740,922,1489,1519]" genus="H." pageId="10" pageNumber="36" rank="species" species="suedico">
<emphasis box="[740,769,1489,1518]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="36">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[791,922,1489,1519]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="36">suedico</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
/ 
<emphasis box="[936,952,1499,1519]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="36">a</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
